Arrowhead is Jo Youngman, a 27-year-old Native American genderfluid individual and member of the Justice Alliance. Prior aliases include Red Arrow, Pink Arrow, Light, and Fletching — a progression that tracked closely with their evolving understanding of their own gender identity. Each name felt right at the time and not quite right enough to keep.

Jo grew up on a reservation in Oklahoma and relocated in their early twenties to compete at the national level in archery. Their competitive career funds their heroics: sponsorships, prize money, and the occasional appearance fee cover equipment and travel without them having to answer uncomfortable questions about where the money goes.

They have no superpowers. What they have is the most accurate eye in any room they walk into, a peak-human level of physical conditioning, and a quiver of specialty arrows — explosive-tip, EMP, grappling line, cryo-burst, and several that haven't been needed yet. They built most of them. They are precise, methodical, and very good at being underestimated.

Jo is aroace, something they are settled and comfortable with. It comes up in therapy primarily in the context of other people's reactions to it: the exhausting repetition of explaining it, the assumption that it must be trauma-based (it isn't), and the occasional teammate who thinks persistent attention will change something. It won't.

Doesn't abuse substances like alcohol or drugs, but occasionally uses pot when trying to calm down before an archery competition. They don't hide it and don't make a thing of it.
